    Wildlife officials, in their consultation with experts from all over the
    world, learned of new research on a antifungal drug for fish that could be
    introduced directly into the water and would immunize the remaining
    crappie population, ending the epidemic. Your team of mathematical
    modelers have been called in to construct a model to help the government
    of Kinakuta decide if the drug strategy will work---before they pay a huge
    of sum of money to get the trials for the drug started---or if they need
    to seek another solution. Wildlife officials have monitored the progress
    of the infection since the beginning of the epidemic 5 months ago. The
    data they have collected since the fungal outbreak began, along with other
    important information is available to your group via the \emph{Conservation Algorithm Network of Vast Aquatic Significance}, known more commonly as
    C.A.N.V.A.S.

\subsection*{Useful facts and assumptions}
\vspace{-2.8ex}

    \begin{compactitem}

        \item The wildlife department at Kinakuta is very vigilant about
        preserving the unique ecosystem of the island and they are very
        confident that they caught the fungus outbreak at its very beginning
        exactly 5 months ago.
        \item Faced with limited scientific information,
        your team has to construct a model for how the fungus is infecting the
        crappie population. Based on past studies, your group has decided to
        try to fit the data from the wildlife department on the rate of
        crappie infection to one of two models, using vector projection. Your
        choice of which model is best will be based on a comparison of
        residual vectors.

        \item The laboratory making the drug warns that if the drug is given
        more than 1 month past the window where the infection rate is maximal,
        the drug will only eradicate the fungus in a certain percentage of infected fish.
        Assume that all the fish that have been infected by the fungus at or
        prior to the time of administration are removed from the population.
        The wildlife department wishes your group to report the number that
        can be saved in all cases.

        % states for the trial to be a success, at least 200 crappie must be
